Note:
This file implements SIZE-CLASS MEMORY POOLS for the Runa runtime memory
system. Pools are a separate concern from arenas: they sit alongside the
chained arena at TIER 3 (OWNED) and provide O(1) allocation and deallocation
for FIXED, FREQUENTLY-USED small allocation sizes.

SIZE-CLASS MEMORY POOLS - O(1) Fixed-Size Bulk Allocation
- Process fixed-size allocations from a pre-batched free list per size class
- Handle 6 size classes (8, 16, 32, 64, 128, 256 bytes) with separate free lists
- Maintain per-batch tracking lists so destroy can free every batch cleanly
- Operate as instance-based pools (no globals) per the MEMORY_ARCHITECTURE.md
  TIER 3 ownership model

This file is essential because of the following reasons:
- Size-class pools serve the small-allocation hot path with constant-time
  allocate/deallocate, which arena bump allocators cannot match for workloads
  that need explicit per-allocation lifetime control.
- Pools reduce fragmentation for frequently-recycled small objects by keeping
  same-size blocks together in dedicated batches.
- Free-list maintenance means the cost of allocate and deallocate is a single
  pointer-update each, independent of pool size and total memory in use.

This file consists of the following functions/features/operation types:
- Size-class index calculation (pool_get_size_class_index)
- Block-size lookup by class index (pool_get_size_for_class)
- Pool lifecycle (pool_create, pool_destroy)
- Batch allocation for empty free lists (pool_allocate_block_batch)
- Allocate / deallocate (pool_allocate, pool_deallocate)
- Statistics access (pool_get_statistics)

Migration note: these primitives were previously part of
`compiler/internal/arena_utils.runa`. They have been moved to this dedicated
file because pools are conceptually distinct from arenas — they serve
different lifetimes (per-allocation vs operation-scoped) and use different
internal data structures (free lists vs bump pointers). No callers existed
at the time of migration (the pool primitives were defined-but-unreferenced),
so the move is name-preserving: every Process keeps its `pool_*` name.

Dependencies:
- Imports compiler/internal/memory_utils.runa for owned-heap allocate/deallocate
- Imports compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa for raw memory r/w
:End Note

Import "compiler/internal/memory_utils.runa" as MemoryUtils
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa" as MemoryCore

Note:
============================================================================
Pool Constants
============================================================================
:End Note

Constant POOL_SIZE_CLASS_COUNT as Integer is 6
Constant POOL_SIZE_8 as Integer is 8
Constant POOL_SIZE_16 as Integer is 16
Constant POOL_SIZE_32 as Integer is 32
Constant POOL_SIZE_64 as Integer is 64
Constant POOL_SIZE_128 as Integer is 128
Constant POOL_SIZE_256 as Integer is 256
Constant POOL_BLOCK_COUNT as Integer is 64

Note:
============================================================================
MemoryPool Structure Definition
============================================================================

MemoryPool instance layout (336 bytes = 6 pool entries * 56 bytes each):

  Per-pool-entry (56 bytes):
    Offset  0: free_list        Pointer to first free block in linked free list
    Offset  8: total_blocks     Total blocks ever allocated for this size class
    Offset 16: free_blocks      Number of blocks currently on the free list
    Offset 24: block_size       Block size in bytes for this class
    Offset 32: allocations      Lifetime allocations served from this class
    Offset 40: deallocations    Lifetime deallocations returned to this class
    Offset 48: batches_list     Head of batch-tracking list (for cleanup)

The pool is instance-based per MEMORY_ARCHITECTURE.md TIER 3 OWNED semantics.
Caller creates the pool via pool_create, retains the returned pointer for the
pool's lifetime, and calls pool_destroy when the pool is no longer needed.
No global state.

Free-list block layout:
  Each block in a free list is prefixed with an 8-byte "next" pointer slot.
  pool_allocate returns the pointer 8 bytes past the block header; the header
  is reused as the next-pointer slot when the block is on the free list.

Batches:
  Blocks are allocated 64 at a time (POOL_BLOCK_COUNT) into a single
  contiguous batch buffer. A separate 16-byte batch-tracking node records
  the batch pointer plus a next-batch-node pointer; nodes are chained from
  the pool entry's batches_list. Destroy walks this list to free every
  batch cleanly with zero leaks.
:End Note

Process called "pool_get_size_class_index" takes size as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Maps a requested allocation size to a pool size class (0..5). Sizes
        that exceed POOL_SIZE_256 cannot be served by any class and the
        caller must fall back to a different allocator (typically arena or
        owned heap). Returning -1 signals this fallback condition rather
        than rounding up indefinitely.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
        A cascade of inclusive upper-bound comparisons: size <= 8 maps to
        class 0, size <= 16 maps to class 1, etc., up to size <= 256 for
        class 5. Anything larger returns -1.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints:
        O(1). Average-case 3 comparisons due to the cascade structure;
        worst-case 6 for the largest fit-in-pool size.
    @End Performance_Hints

    If size is less than or equal to POOL_SIZE_8:
        Return 0
    Otherwise If size is less than or equal to POOL_SIZE_16:
        Return 1
    Otherwise If size is less than or equal to POOL_SIZE_32:
        Return 2
    Otherwise If size is less than or equal to POOL_SIZE_64:
        Return 3
    Otherwise If size is less than or equal to POOL_SIZE_128:
        Return 4
    Otherwise If size is less than or equal to POOL_SIZE_256:
        Return 5
    End If

    Return negative 1
End Process

Process called "pool_get_size_for_class" takes class_index as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Inverse of pool_get_size_class_index. Returns the actual block size
        backing each class index. Used during pool initialization to write
        block_size into each pool entry.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
        A direct lookup by index 0..5; out-of-range indices return 0 so
        callers can detect the error condition.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints:
        O(1). Average-case 3 comparisons due to cascade structure.
    @End Performance_Hints

    If class_index is equal to 0:
        Return POOL_SIZE_8
    Otherwise If class_index is equal to 1:
        Return POOL_SIZE_16
    Otherwise If class_index is equal to 2:
        Return POOL_SIZE_32
    Otherwise If class_index is equal to 3:
        Return POOL_SIZE_64
    Otherwise If class_index is equal to 4:
        Return POOL_SIZE_128
    Otherwise If class_index is equal to 5:
        Return POOL_SIZE_256
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

Process called "pool_create" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Creates an instance-based MemoryPool with all 6 size classes
        initialized to empty free lists. The instance model lets multiple
        pools coexist (per-thread, per-subsystem) without any global state.
        Allocation of actual block batches is deferred to the first call
        into pool_allocate for a given class — pools start empty and only
        allocate memory on demand.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
        Steps:
            1. Allocate the 336-byte pool structure on the owned heap.
            2. For each class_index in 0..5:
                 - Compute pool_entry_ptr = pool + class_index * 56.
                 - Look up block_size via pool_get_size_for_class.
                 - Zero the free_list, total_blocks, free_blocks,
                   allocations, deallocations, and batches_list fields.
                 - Write block_size into the entry's block_size field.
            3. Return the pool pointer (or 0 on allocation failure).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints:
        Single owned-heap allocation plus 6*7 = 42 memory writes. Performed
        once per pool lifetime.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope:
        Pool ownership transfers to the caller; caller must invoke
        pool_destroy on cleanup. No global pool registration occurs.
    @End Security_Scope

    Note: Allocate pool structure (6 classes * 56 bytes per entry = 336 bytes)
    Let pool_struct_size be 336
    Let pool be proc allocate from MemoryUtils with pool_struct_size

    If pool is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Initialize each pool size class
    Let class_index be 0
    While class_index is less than POOL_SIZE_CLASS_COUNT:
        Let pool_entry_offset be class_index multiplied by 56
        Let pool_entry_ptr be pool plus pool_entry_offset

        Note: Get block size for this class
        Let block_size be proc pool_get_size_for_class with class_index

        Note: Initialize pool entry fields
        Let dummy1 be proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with pool_entry_ptr, 0, 0             Note: free_list = null
        Let dummy2 be proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with pool_entry_ptr, 8, 0             Note: total_blocks = 0
        Let dummy3 be proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with pool_entry_ptr, 16, 0            Note: free_blocks = 0
        Let dummy4 be proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with pool_entry_ptr, 24, block_size   Note: block_size
        Let dummy5 be proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with pool_entry_ptr, 32, 0            Note: allocations = 0
        Let dummy6 be proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with pool_entry_ptr, 40, 0            Note: deallocations = 0
        Let dummy7 be proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with pool_entry_ptr, 48, 0            Note: batches_list = null

        Set class_index to class_index plus 1
    End While

    Return pool
End Process

Process called "pool_allocate_block_batch" takes pool as Integer, class_index as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        When a pool entry's free list is empty, this routine allocates a
        contiguous batch of 64 blocks, threads them into a free list, and
        records the batch in the entry's batches_list so destroy can free it
        cleanly. Batch allocation amortizes the per-block allocate cost
        across 64 blocks.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
        Steps:
            1. NULL pool guard and class_index range check [0, POOL_SIZE_CLASS_COUNT).
            2. Compute pool_entry_ptr.
            3. Read block_size; compute actual_block_size = block_size + 8
               (room for the 8-byte next pointer prefix).
            4. Allocate the batch buffer: actual_block_size * POOL_BLOCK_COUNT.
            5. Allocate a 16-byte batch-tracking node.
            6. If either allocation fails, free what was allocated and return 0.
            7. Initialize the batch node (batch_ptr, next=null), then prepend
               it onto pool_entry.batches_list.
            8. Thread the 64 blocks into a free list by writing each block's
               next pointer to point at the next block in the batch.
            9. Prepend the new batch to the existing free list (set the last
               block's next to the old free list head, set the entry's
               free_list to the first block of the batch).
            10. Update total_blocks += POOL_BLOCK_COUNT and
                free_blocks += POOL_BLOCK_COUNT.
            11. Return POOL_BLOCK_COUNT.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints:
        One large owned-heap allocation (block batch), one small node
        allocation, and O(POOL_BLOCK_COUNT) memory writes to thread the
        free list. Amortizes the per-block cost across 64 subsequent
        pool_allocate calls.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope:
        Batch-tracking ensures destroy can find every batch. If batch
        tracking were omitted, batches allocated after pool_create would
        leak on destroy. The 16-byte node cost per 64-block batch is the
        price of correct cleanup.
    @End Security_Scope

    If pool is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    If class_index is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    If class_index is greater than or equal to POOL_SIZE_CLASS_COUNT:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Get pool entry
    Let pool_entry_offset be class_index multiplied by 56
    Let pool_entry_ptr be pool plus pool_entry_offset

    Note: Get block size for this class
    Let block_size be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with pool_entry_ptr, 24

    Note: Add 8 bytes for next pointer in free list
    Let actual_block_size be block_size plus 8

    Note: Allocate batch of blocks
    Let batch_size be actual_block_size multiplied by POOL_BLOCK_COUNT
    Let batch_ptr be proc allocate from MemoryUtils with batch_size

    If batch_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Allocate batch tracking node (16 bytes: batch_ptr + next)
    Let batch_node_size be 16
    Let batch_node be proc allocate from MemoryUtils with batch_node_size

    If batch_node is equal to 0:
        Let dummy_free_batch be proc deallocate from MemoryUtils with batch_ptr
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Initialize batch tracking node
    Let dummy_bn1 be proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with batch_node, 0, batch_ptr  Note: batch_ptr
    Let dummy_bn2 be proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with batch_node, 8, 0          Note: next = null

    Note: Add batch node to batches_list (prepend)
    Let old_batches_list be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with pool_entry_ptr, 48
    Let dummy_bn3 be proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with batch_node, 8, old_batches_list
    Let dummy_bn4 be proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with pool_entry_ptr, 48, batch_node

    Note: Initialize free list by linking all blocks
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than POOL_BLOCK_COUNT:
        Let block_offset be i multiplied by actual_block_size
        Let block_ptr be batch_ptr plus block_offset

        Note: Calculate next block pointer
        Let next_block_ptr be 0
        Let next_i be i plus 1
        If next_i is less than POOL_BLOCK_COUNT:
            Let next_block_offset be next_i multiplied by actual_block_size
            Set next_block_ptr to batch_ptr plus next_block_offset
        End If

        Note: Set next pointer in block (first 8 bytes)
        Let dummy_next be proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with block_ptr, 0, next_block_ptr

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Update pool entry to add new blocks to free list (prepend batch)
    Let old_free_list be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with pool_entry_ptr, 0
    Let dummy_set_free be proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with pool_entry_ptr, 0, batch_ptr

    Note: Link old free list to end of new blocks
    If old_free_list is not equal to 0:
        Note: Find last block in new batch
        Let last_block_offset be POOL_BLOCK_COUNT minus 1
        Set last_block_offset to last_block_offset multiplied by actual_block_size
        Let last_block_ptr be batch_ptr plus last_block_offset

        Note: Link to old free list
        Let dummy_link be proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with last_block_ptr, 0, old_free_list
    End If

    Note: Update statistics
    Let old_total_blocks be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with pool_entry_ptr, 8
    Let new_total_blocks be old_total_blocks plus POOL_BLOCK_COUNT
    Let dummy_total be proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with pool_entry_ptr, 8, new_total_blocks

    Let old_free_blocks be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with pool_entry_ptr, 16
    Let new_free_blocks be old_free_blocks plus POOL_BLOCK_COUNT
    Let dummy_free be proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with pool_entry_ptr, 16, new_free_blocks

    Return POOL_BLOCK_COUNT
End Process

Process called "pool_allocate" takes pool as Integer, size as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        The primary entry point for pool allocation. Maps the requested size
        to a class, ensures the free list has at least one block (triggering
        a batch allocation if it is empty), pops the head of the free list,
        and returns a pointer to the usable memory (past the 8-byte next-pointer
        prefix). Returns 0 if the size exceeds any pool class; the caller is
        expected to fall back to another allocator in that case.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
        Steps:
            1. NULL pool guard.
            2. class_index = pool_get_size_class_index(size). If -1, return 0.
            3. Compute pool_entry_ptr.
            4. Read free_blocks. If 0, call pool_allocate_block_batch.
               If batch returns 0, return 0 (allocation failed at runtime).
            5. Read free_list_head. Return 0 if NULL (defense in depth;
               should not happen after a successful batch).
            6. Read free_list_head.next (the new head after popping).
            7. Write the new head into pool_entry.free_list.
            8. Decrement free_blocks; increment allocations.
            9. Return free_list_head + 8 (skip the 8-byte next-pointer prefix).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints:
        Hot path: 4 memory reads + 3 memory writes, all O(1). When the free
        list is empty the cost spikes to one batch allocation amortized over
        64 subsequent allocations.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope:
        Returns a pointer into pool-owned memory. The pointer is valid until
        the caller passes it back to pool_deallocate or the pool is destroyed.
        Callers must not retain pointers past pool destruction.
    @End Security_Scope

    If pool is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Check if size fits in any pool class
    Let class_index be proc pool_get_size_class_index with size

    If class_index is less than 0:
        Note: Size too large for pooling - caller must fall back
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Get pool entry for this size class
    Let pool_entry_offset be class_index multiplied by 56
    Let pool_entry_ptr be pool plus pool_entry_offset

    Note: Check if free blocks available
    Let free_blocks be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with pool_entry_ptr, 16

    If free_blocks is equal to 0:
        Note: No free blocks, allocate new batch
        Let batch_count be proc pool_allocate_block_batch with pool, class_index

        If batch_count is equal to 0:
            Note: Failed to allocate batch
            Return 0
        End If

        Note: Reload free_blocks after batch allocation
        Set free_blocks to proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with pool_entry_ptr, 16
    End If

    Note: Get first block from free list
    Let free_list_head be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with pool_entry_ptr, 0

    If free_list_head is equal to 0:
        Note: Free list is empty (should not happen after batch allocation)
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Read next pointer from block (first 8 bytes)
    Let next_free_block be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with free_list_head, 0

    Note: Update free list head to next block
    Let dummy_update_head be proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with pool_entry_ptr, 0, next_free_block

    Note: Update statistics
    Let new_free_blocks be free_blocks minus 1
    Let dummy_free_count be proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with pool_entry_ptr, 16, new_free_blocks

    Let allocations be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with pool_entry_ptr, 32
    Let new_allocations be allocations plus 1
    Let dummy_alloc_count be proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with pool_entry_ptr, 32, new_allocations

    Note: Return pointer to usable memory (skip 8-byte header)
    Let usable_ptr be free_list_head plus 8

    Return usable_ptr
End Process

Process called "pool_deallocate" takes pool as Integer, ptr as Integer, size as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Returns a previously-allocated block to its pool's free list. Pushes
        the block at the head of the free list so subsequent allocations
        reuse it (LIFO discipline keeps recently-touched memory hot in cache).
        The size parameter is required so we can identify which class the
        block belongs to without storing per-block class metadata.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
        Steps:
            1. NULL pool/ptr guard.
            2. class_index = pool_get_size_class_index(size); return 0 if -1.
            3. Compute pool_entry_ptr and the block_header_ptr (= ptr - 8).
            4. Read the current free_list head.
            5. Write block_header_ptr.next = current head.
            6. Write pool_entry.free_list = block_header_ptr.
            7. Increment free_blocks, increment deallocations.
            8. Return 1.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints:
        Hot path: 3 memory reads + 3 memory writes, all O(1). LIFO push at
        the head of the free list.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope:
        The pointer must have come from a prior pool_allocate against the
        same pool with the same size; passing a foreign pointer corrupts
        the free list. The class_index resolution is done by size, so the
        size argument must match what was passed to allocate. There is no
        runtime check against this constraint — it is a caller responsibility.
    @End Security_Scope

    If pool is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    If ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Check if size fits in any pool class
    Let class_index be proc pool_get_size_class_index with size

    If class_index is less than 0:
        Note: Size doesn't match any pool class - cannot deallocate
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Get pool entry for this size class
    Let pool_entry_offset be class_index multiplied by 56
    Let pool_entry_ptr be pool plus pool_entry_offset

    Note: Get block header pointer (subtract 8 bytes for next-pointer prefix)
    Let block_header_ptr be ptr minus 8

    Note: Get current free list head
    Let free_list_head be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with pool_entry_ptr, 0

    Note: Set next pointer in returned block to current head
    Let dummy_next be proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with block_header_ptr, 0, free_list_head

    Note: Update free list head to returned block
    Let dummy_head be proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with pool_entry_ptr, 0, block_header_ptr

    Note: Update statistics
    Let free_blocks be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with pool_entry_ptr, 16
    Let new_free_blocks be free_blocks plus 1
    Let dummy_free_count be proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with pool_entry_ptr, 16, new_free_blocks

    Let deallocations be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with pool_entry_ptr, 40
    Let new_deallocations be deallocations plus 1
    Let dummy_dealloc_count be proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with pool_entry_ptr, 40, new_deallocations

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "pool_get_statistics" takes pool as Integer, class_index as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Returns a pointer to the pool entry for the requested class. Every
        diagnostic counter lives inside that 56-byte entry, so callers get
        all statistics through one pointer rather than seven separate
        getters. The returned pointer aliases the internal pool entry;
        callers must not mutate it and must not retain it past pool_destroy.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
        Steps:
            1. NULL pool guard and class_index range check.
            2. Compute pool_entry_ptr = pool + class_index * 56.
            3. Return pool_entry_ptr.
        Callers read the same fields documented in this file's header
        (free_list, total_blocks, free_blocks, block_size, allocations,
        deallocations, batches_list) via memory_get_integer.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints:
        O(1). Pure pointer arithmetic.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope:
        The returned pointer is internal to the pool. Treat it as read-only
        and do not free it. It becomes invalid after pool_destroy.
    @End Security_Scope

    If pool is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    If class_index is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    If class_index is greater than or equal to POOL_SIZE_CLASS_COUNT:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Return pointer to pool entry (contains all statistics)
    Let pool_entry_offset be class_index multiplied by 56
    Let pool_entry_ptr be pool plus pool_entry_offset

    Return pool_entry_ptr
End Process

Process called "pool_destroy" takes pool as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Tears down the pool with zero memory leaks. The critical correctness
        property here is that EVERY batch ever allocated must be freed, not
        just the ones referenced from free lists. That is why each batch is
        recorded in batches_list on creation — destroy walks that list per
        class and frees every batch buffer and tracking node before freeing
        the pool structure itself.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
        Steps:
            1. NULL pool guard.
            2. For each class_index in 0..POOL_SIZE_CLASS_COUNT:
                 - Compute pool_entry_ptr.
                 - Read batches_list from offset 48.
                 - Walk the batch-tracking list:
                     - Read batch_ptr (offset 0) and next_batch_node (offset 8).
                     - Free batch_ptr (if non-null) via MemoryUtils.deallocate.
                     - Free the tracking node itself.
                     - Advance to next_batch_node.
            3. Free the pool structure itself.
            4. Return 1.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints:
        O(total_batch_count) across all classes. Each batch is freed exactly
        once. Cost is dominated by the underlying allocator's per-free cost.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope:
        Invalidates EVERY pointer ever returned from this pool. Callers must
        not retain or use such pointers after destroy. This is non-negotiable
        because the underlying batch memory is returned to the heap.
    @End Security_Scope

    If pool is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Walk through all 6 size classes and free their batches
    Let class_index be 0
    While class_index is less than POOL_SIZE_CLASS_COUNT:
        Let pool_entry_offset be class_index multiplied by 56
        Let pool_entry_ptr be pool plus pool_entry_offset

        Note: Get batches_list for this size class
        Let batches_list be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with pool_entry_ptr, 48

        Note: Walk through batches_list and free all batches
        Let current_batch_node be batches_list
        While current_batch_node is not equal to 0:
            Note: Get batch pointer and next node
            Let batch_ptr be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with current_batch_node, 0
            Let next_batch_node be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with current_batch_node, 8

            Note: Free the actual batch memory
            If batch_ptr is not equal to 0:
                Let dummy_free_batch be proc deallocate from MemoryUtils with batch_ptr
            End If

            Note: Free the batch tracking node
            Let dummy_free_node be proc deallocate from MemoryUtils with current_batch_node

            Note: Move to next batch node
            Set current_batch_node to next_batch_node
        End While

        Set class_index to class_index plus 1
    End While

    Note: Free the pool structure itself
    Let dummy_free_pool be proc deallocate from MemoryUtils with pool

    Return 1
End Process

Note:
============================================================================
END OF SIZE-CLASS MEMORY POOL IMPLEMENTATION
============================================================================
:End Note
